<div id="review_2514410267" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2514410267" />
    <a title="Missy (myweereads)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29477737-missy-myweereads"><img alt="Missy (myweereads)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1598204465p2/29477737.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2514410267?book_show_action=true">Aug 31, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Missy (myweereads)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Missy (myweereads)" href="/user/show/29477737-missy-myweereads">Missy (myweereads)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780060291709" href="/book/show/673206.Abarat">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2514410267" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6837489874968628016">“Any fool can be happy. It takes a man with real heart to make beauty out of the stuff that makes us weep.”<br/><br/>Abarat - Days Of Magic, Nights Of War by Clive Barker is the second book in this series. It’s the continuing story of Candy Quackenbush’s adventures in this amazing world. Carrion has sent his men to capture Candy however she is wondering why her? why does this place feel very familiar? and how is she able to recite words of magic which were previously unheard of to her. Carrion’s grandmoth</span>
  <span id="freeText6837489874968628016" style="display:none">“Any fool can be happy. It takes a man with real heart to make beauty out of the stuff that makes us weep.”<br /><br />Abarat - Days Of Magic, Nights Of War by Clive Barker is the second book in this series. It’s the continuing story of Candy Quackenbush’s adventures in this amazing world. Carrion has sent his men to capture Candy however she is wondering why her? why does this place feel very familiar? and how is she able to recite words of magic which were previously unheard of to her. Carrion’s grandmother sees Candy as a threat to her dominion over Abarat and therefore Candy’s friends fight to save her from them and to avoid Absolute Darkness to descend upon the Islands forever.<br /><br />What can I say that I haven’t said before about Clive Barker’s epic adventures. This is a magical world which brings fantasy and horrors to reality and both scares and pleases the reader, connecting them to this journey Candy Quackenbush is on. This book picks up where the first one left off and we are again at a never ending crossroads of finding out the truth behind the mysterious Abarat.<br /><br />Barker once again brings the cast of crazy and outlandish demonic and playful characters throughout this story. My favourite villain Christopher Carrion is back as evil as ever along with his grandmother known as Mater Motley who is evil personified. I was happy to see the cheeky John Mischief and his siblings also Malingo. <br />.<br />The descriptions of the islands is translated beautifully not just through Barker’s prose but also his illustrations. Each image adds magic to the story being told and brings to life the fantasy and evil which laces this adventure. The need to know what happens next is present from the minute you read the first chapter. This was a re-read for me which was long overdue and I couldn’t put this book down. I was reminded of a world which I was able to escape in and never wanted to come back from.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6837489874968628016" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


